ing whose name might have been Romulus founded Rome one April 21st in the mid-eighth century BC, most likely in a ceremony in which a white bull and cow pulled a plow to trace the position of a wall marking the blessed soil of the new city. This ceremony establishing the Palatine Wall, which Carandini discovered, inaugurated the political life of a city that, through its later empire, would influence much of the world. Uncovering the birth of a city that gave birth to a world, Rome: Day One reveals as never before a truly epochal event.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aArchaeology and historyzItalyzRome. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zItalyzRome. 0aMythology, Roman. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh1 aSartarelli, Stephen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400838066zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400838066423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400838066/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK